The '''Italian destroyer ''Audace''''' was originally ordered by Japan from [[Yarrow Shipbuilders]] in Scotland under the name of ''Kawakaze'', but was transferred to Italy in 1916 while still under construction. She served as the command ship for the radio-controlled [[target ship]] {{ship|Italian cruiser|San Marco||2}} in 1937–40 and then was rearmed for [[convoy]] escort and patrolling duties when World War II began. ''Audace'' was captured by the Germans in 1943 and used by them as a [[minelayer]] and escort ship in the [[Adriatic Sea]] until she was sunk by a pair of British destroyers in late 1944.

==Design and description==
''Audace'' had a [[length between perpendiculars]] of {{convert|83.9|m|ftin|sp=us}} and an [[length overall|overall length]] of {{convert|87.59|m|ftin|sp=us}}. She had a [[beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|8.38|m|ftin|sp=us}} and a [[draft (hull)|draft]] of {{convert|2.5|m|ftin|sp=us}}. The ship displaced {{convert|922|t|LT|sp=us}} at normal load, and {{convert|1170|t|LT|sp=us}} at [[deep load]]. Her complement was 5 officers and 113 enlisted men.<ref name=f8>Fraccaroli, p. 72</ref>

The ship was powered by two [[John Brown & Company|Brown-Curtis]] [[steam turbine]]s, each driving one propeller shaft using steam supplied by 3 [[Yarrow boiler]]s. Designed for a maximum output of {{convert|22000|shp|lk=in}} and a speed of {{convert|30|kn|lk=in}}, ''Audace'' handily exceeded this, reaching a speed of {{convert|34.5|kn}} during her [[sea trial]]s while lightly loaded. Her intended German-built diesel cruising engines were not delivered because of the war. She had a cruising range of {{convert|2180|nmi|lk=in}} at a speed of {{convert|15|kn}} and {{convert|560|nmi|lk=in}} at a speed of {{convert|30|kn}}.<ref name=g0>Gardiner & Gray, p. 269</ref>

Only two [[List of British ordnance terms#QF|quick-firing (QF)]] 39-[[caliber (artillery)|caliber]] [[QF 2-pounder naval gun|two-pounder]] [[anti-aircraft gun]]s had been installed before the ship was transferred to Italy in 1916.<ref name=f8/> The gun fired its {{convert|40|mm|adj=on|sp=us}}, {{convert|2|lb|disp=flip|sp=us|adj=on}}, [[Explosive material#High explosives|high-explosive]] shells at a [[muzzle velocity]] of {{convert|2040|ft/s|m/s|sp=us|disp=flip}}.<ref>Friedman, p. 119</ref> The ship's main armament consisted of seven QF [[Cannone da 76/35 S Modello 1914–15]] guns in single mounts.<ref name=g0/> This gun fired a {{convert|30.31|lb|kg|adj=on|disp=flip|sp=us}} projectile at a muzzle velocity of {{convert|755|m/s|sp=us|disp=flip}}.<ref>Friedman, p. 241</ref> ''Audace'' was also equipped with four {{convert|450|mm|in|adj=on|sp=us|1}} [[torpedo tube]]s in twin mounts, one on each [[broadside]].<ref name=g0/>

==Construction and career==
The [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] ordered a pair of {{sclass-|Urakaze|destroyer}}s from the British [[Yarrow Shipbuilders]] in 1913, and ''Kawakaze'' (as the ship was originally named) was [[keel laying|laid down]] on 1 October 1913 at their [[Scotstoun]] shipyard. Construction was delayed by a backlog of previous orders and then by the outbreak of World War I in August 1914.<ref>Fraccaroli, pp. 72, 74</ref> The Italians, desperately short of destroyers, began negotiations with the Japanese to acquire ''Kawakaze'' and succeeded on 3 July 1916 when they agreed to transfer the ship. The ''Regia Marina'' named their new acquisition ''Intrepido'' two days later, but renamed her ''Audace'' on 25 September.<ref name=g0/> She was [[Ship naming and launching|launched]] on 27 September and completed on 1 March 1917.<ref name=f4>Fraccaroli, p. 74</ref>

''Audace'' was reclassified as a [[torpedo boat]] on 1 September 1929 and was modified to serve as the command ship of the radio-controlled target ship ''San Marco'' from 1937–40.<ref name=f4/> She was rearmed in 1940 for escort duties with her main armament reduced to three 102-millimeter guns. In 1943 one 102-millimeter gun and the two 2-pounder AA guns were replaced by five {{convert|20|mm|abbr=on}}/65 [[Breda Model 35]] [[autocannon]] in single mounts.<ref name=b4>Brescia, pp. 136–37</ref>

The non-operational ship was captured on 12 September when the Germans occupied [[Venice]] and they redesignated her as ''TA 20''. They augmented her anti-aircraft armament to 20 Breda guns in 10 twin mounts and assigned her to escort and minelaying work in the Adriatic Sea.<ref>Brescia, p. 137</ref> On 15 March 1944, she laid a minefield south of [[Ancona]] and others east of San Giorgio on the night of 17/18 and 29 March. The British destroyers {{HMS|Wheatland||2}} and {{HMS|Avon Vale|L06|2}} [[Action of 1 November 1944|ambushed and sank]] ''TA 20'' and two accompanying [[corvette]]s on 1 November south of [[Lussino]] in the Adriatic.<ref>Rohwer, pp. 312, 370</ref>

